  const ENTRIES = [

    /* ════════════ GEOGRAPHY ════════════ */
    { id: 'ring-of-fire', topic: 'Geography', title: 'The Ring of Fire', category: 'Tectonics', summary: 'A horseshoe-shaped belt around the Pacific Ocean where most of the world\'s earthquakes and volcanic eruptions occur.', content: 'The Ring of Fire traces the boundaries of the Pacific Plate as it grinds against surrounding plates — the Nazca, Cocos, North American, Eurasian, Philippine, and Indo-Australian plates. This roughly 40,000 km arc runs from New Zealand up through Indonesia, Japan, the Aleutians, and down the west coast of the Americas to Chile. It is not a single fault but a chain of subduction zones, where one plate is forced beneath another, generating both deep earthquakes and the magma that feeds volcanic arcs.', highlights: ['Roughly 40,000 km long', 'Hosts about 75% of the world\'s active and dormant volcanoes', 'Around 90% of all earthquakes occur along it', 'Formed by subduction of the Pacific Plate beneath neighboring plates', 'Includes Japan, Indonesia, the Philippines, and the US West Coast'] },
    { id: 'sahara-desert', topic: 'Geography', title: 'The Sahara Desert', category: 'Deserts', summary: 'The world\'s largest hot desert, roughly the size of the United States, and a desert that was lush grassland only 6,000 years ago.', content: 'The Sahara spans over 9 million km² across North Africa, touching eleven countries. Despite its image as endless dunes, only about 25% is sand sea — the rest is rocky plateau, gravel plains, and mountains, including the Ahaggar and Tibesti ranges. During the "African Humid Period" (roughly 11,000–5,000 years ago), the region was a savanna with lakes, rivers, and hippos, evidenced by rock art depicting giraffes and cattle herding. A shift in Earth\'s orbital tilt and weakening monsoon dried it into the desert we know today.', highlights: ['Covers over 9 million km² — nearly the size of the USA or China', 'Only about 25% of it is sand dunes; the rest is rock and gravel', 'Was a green savanna with lakes until about 5,000 years ago', 'Contains the Ahaggar and Tibesti mountain ranges', 'Daytime temperatures can exceed 50°C (122°F)'] },
    { id: 'amazon-rainforest', topic: 'Geography', title: 'The Amazon Rainforest', category: 'Ecosystems', summary: 'The largest tropical rainforest on Earth, producing roughly 20% of the planet\'s river discharge into the ocean.', content: 'The Amazon basin covers about 5.5 million km² across nine countries, with roughly 60% in Brazil. It holds an estimated 390 billion individual trees from 16,000 species, and the Amazon River itself discharges more water than the next seven largest rivers combined. The forest plays an outsized role in global carbon storage and regional rainfall — much of the moisture that falls as rain over the basin is recycled by the forest itself through transpiration, a phenomenon sometimes called "flying rivers."', highlights: ['Covers about 5.5 million km² across nine South American countries', 'Home to an estimated 390 billion trees of 16,000 species', 'The Amazon River discharges more water than the next 7 largest rivers combined', 'Generates much of its own rainfall through forest transpiration', 'Holds roughly 10% of the world\'s known species'] },
    { id: 'strait-of-malacca', topic: 'Geography', title: 'The Strait of Malacca', category: 'Trade chokepoints', summary: 'A narrow waterway between Malaysia/Sumatra that carries roughly a quarter of all global maritime trade.', content: 'At its narrowest point, the Phillips Channel, the Strait of Malacca is only about 2.8 km wide, yet an estimated 25% of all globally traded goods — and a similar share of the world\'s oil shipments — pass through it each year en route between the Indian Ocean and the South China Sea. Its narrowness makes it a strategic chokepoint: any disruption (piracy, blockade, or accident) can ripple through global shipping costs, which is why countries like China have invested heavily in alternative routes such as pipelines through Myanmar.', highlights: ['Narrows to about 2.8 km wide at the Phillips Channel', 'Carries an estimated 25% of all global maritime trade', 'Connects the Indian Ocean to the South China Sea / Pacific', 'A major chokepoint for global oil shipments', 'Strategic vulnerability has driven China to build alternate pipeline routes'] },
    { id: 'himalayas-everest', topic: 'Geography', title: 'The Himalayas & Mount Everest', category: 'Mountains', summary: 'The world\'s highest mountain range, still rising a few millimeters a year as India collides with Asia.', content: 'The Himalayas formed roughly 50 million years ago when the Indian tectonic plate, drifting north after breaking from Gondwana, collided with the Eurasian plate. That collision is still happening — the range rises about 5mm per year, even as erosion wears it down. Mount Everest, on the Nepal–China border, stands at 8,849m (29,032 ft) by the most recent official measurement (2020), a figure jointly confirmed by Nepal and China after decades of slightly differing surveys.', highlights: ['Formed ~50 million years ago by the India–Eurasia plate collision', 'Still rising roughly 5mm per year', 'Mount Everest\'s official height is 8,849m (2020 joint Nepal–China survey)', 'Contains over 100 peaks exceeding 7,200m', 'Acts as a climate barrier separating the Indian monsoon from Central Asia'] },
    { id: 'great-rift-valley', topic: 'Geography', title: 'The Great Rift Valley', category: 'Tectonics', summary: 'A 6,000 km tectonic scar across East Africa where the continent is slowly splitting in two.', content: 'The East African Rift is a developing divergent plate boundary where the Somali Plate is pulling away from the much larger Nubian (African) Plate at a rate of a few millimeters per year. Over the next 5–10 million years, geologists expect the rift to widen into a new ocean basin, eventually separating a "Somali continent" from the rest of Africa. The rift is also famous for its role in human evolution — many of the oldest hominid fossils, including "Lucy," were found in its sediment layers.', highlights: ['Stretches roughly 6,000 km from the Red Sea to Mozambique', 'A divergent boundary that may eventually split Africa into two continents', 'Widening at a few millimeters per year', 'Site of major hominid fossil discoveries, including "Lucy"', 'Contains many of Africa\'s deepest lakes, including Lake Tanganyika'] },
    { id: 'arctic-permafrost', topic: 'Geography', title: 'Permafrost & the Arctic', category: 'Polar regions', summary: 'Ground that has stayed frozen for at least two years, underlying nearly a quarter of the Northern Hemisphere\'s land.', content: 'Permafrost covers about 23 million km² — roughly 24% of exposed land in the Northern Hemisphere — across Siberia, Alaska, northern Canada, and parts of the Tibetan Plateau. It locks away an estimated 1,500 billion tonnes of carbon in frozen organic matter, almost twice what is currently in the atmosphere. As global temperatures rise, thawing permafrost risks releasing methane and CO2 in a feedback loop, while also destabilizing roads, pipelines, and buildings built on what was once solid frozen ground.', highlights: ['Covers about 24% of Northern Hemisphere land', 'Stores an estimated 1,500 billion tonnes of carbon — nearly 2x atmospheric CO2', 'Thawing risks a methane/CO2 feedback loop that accelerates warming', 'Destabilizes infrastructure built on previously solid frozen ground', 'Some permafrost has remained frozen for hundreds of thousands of years'] },
    { id: 'nile-river', topic: 'Geography', title: 'The Nile River', category: 'Rivers', summary: 'Long disputed as the world\'s longest river, the Nile flows north and has shaped Egyptian civilization for 5,000 years.', content: 'The Nile flows roughly 6,650 km from its sources in the African Great Lakes region (the White Nile) and the Ethiopian Highlands (the Blue Nile) north to the Mediterranean — unusual because most major rivers flow toward the equator, not away from it. Ancient Egyptian civilization depended on its predictable annual flooding, which deposited nutrient-rich silt across the Nile Valley. Today the river is shared by 11 countries, and the Grand Ethiopian Renaissance Dam has become a major source of diplomatic tension with downstream Egypt and Sudan.', highlights: ['Flows roughly 6,650 km — among the longest rivers on Earth', 'Flows north, fed by the White Nile and Blue Nile', 'Ancient Egypt\'s agriculture depended on its annual flood cycle', 'Shared by 11 countries today', 'The Grand Ethiopian Renaissance Dam is a major source of regional tension'] },
    { id: 'pangaea-plate-tectonics', topic: 'Geography', title: 'Pangaea & Plate Tectonics', category: 'Tectonics', summary: 'The supercontinent that began breaking apart 175 million years ago, explaining why continents fit together like puzzle pieces.', content: 'Pangaea formed about 335 million years ago when nearly all of Earth\'s landmasses fused into a single supercontinent surrounded by one vast ocean, Panthalassa. It began rifting apart roughly 175 million years ago, first splitting into Laurasia (north) and Gondwana (south), which then fragmented further into the continents we recognize today. The theory of plate tectonics — that Earth\'s crust is broken into plates that drift on the molten mantle below — wasn\'t broadly accepted until the 1960s, decades after Alfred Wegener first proposed continental drift in 1912 and was largely dismissed by his peers.', highlights: ['Pangaea formed roughly 335 million years ago', 'Began breaking apart about 175 million years ago', 'Split first into Laurasia and Gondwana, then into today\'s continents', 'Alfred Wegener proposed continental drift in 1912 — dismissed for decades', 'Plate tectonics wasn\'t widely accepted until the 1960s'] },
    { id: 'time-zones-date-line', topic: 'Geography', title: 'Time Zones & the International Date Line', category: 'Geopolitics of time', summary: 'An imaginary line near 180° longitude where crossing east or west changes the calendar date by a full day.', content: 'The International Date Line roughly follows the 180th meridian but zigzags to avoid splitting countries across two dates — it bends around Kiribati, Russia\'s Chukotka, and other territories. Crossing it westbound (e.g., flying from the US to Asia) skips a day forward; crossing it eastbound adds a day back. Kiribati moved its easternmost islands to the western side of the line in 1995 specifically so the entire country could share the same date, briefly making it the first place on Earth to reach each new year.', highlights: ['Roughly follows 180° longitude but zigzags around national borders', 'Crossing westbound skips a calendar day forward', 'Kiribati shifted its territory across the line in 1995 to unify its date', 'World time zones span a 24-hour range relative to UTC', 'Some time zones use 30 or 45-minute offsets, not just whole hours'] },
    { id: 'mariana-trench', topic: 'Geography', title: 'The Mariana Trench', category: 'Oceans', summary: 'The deepest point in any of Earth\'s oceans, plunging nearly 11 km below the surface in the Pacific.', content: 'The Challenger Deep, within the Mariana Trench near Guam, reaches a depth of about 10,935m — deep enough that if Mount Everest were placed at its bottom, its peak would still sit over 2 km underwater. The trench formed where the Pacific Plate subducts beneath the smaller Mariana Plate. Only a handful of crewed descents have ever reached the bottom, starting with Jacques Piccard and Don Walsh in 1960, followed decades later by filmmaker James Cameron in 2012.', highlights: ['Challenger Deep reaches about 10,935m below sea level', 'Mount Everest would be submerged by over 2km if placed inside it', 'Formed by subduction of the Pacific Plate beneath the Mariana Plate', 'First reached by crewed submersible in 1960 (Piccard and Walsh)', 'James Cameron made a solo descent to the bottom in 2012'] },
    { id: 'landlocked-enclaves', topic: 'Geography', title: 'Landlocked Countries & Enclaves', category: 'Political geography', summary: 'Some nations have no coastline at all, and a few sit entirely surrounded by a single other country.', content: 'There are 44 landlocked countries in the world, including two "doubly landlocked" nations — Liechtenstein and Uzbekistan — which are surrounded only by other landlocked countries, meaning goods must cross at least two borders to reach the sea. Even more unusual are countries that sit entirely enclosed within a single other state: Lesotho is completely surrounded by South Africa, and San Marino and Vatican City are entirely surrounded by Italy. These geographic quirks create unique trade, legal, and diplomatic relationships with the surrounding nation.', highlights: ['44 countries in the world are landlocked', 'Liechtenstein and Uzbekistan are "doubly landlocked"', 'Lesotho is entirely surrounded by South Africa', 'San Marino and Vatican City sit entirely within Italy', 'Landlocked status often shapes trade dependency on neighboring states'] },

    /* ════════════ POLITICS ════════════ */
    { id: 'separation-of-powers', topic: 'Politics', title: 'Separation of Powers', category: 'Constitutional design', summary: 'A system that splits government into legislative, executive, and judicial branches so no single branch holds unchecked authority.', content: 'Formalized by Montesquieu in his 1748 work "The Spirit of the Laws," the separation of powers divides government into three branches — the legislature (makes laws), the executive (enforces laws), and the judiciary (interprets laws) — each able to check the others. The US Constitution embeds this through mechanisms like presidential veto power, congressional override of vetoes, judicial review, and Senate confirmation of judicial appointments. Not all democracies separate powers this rigidly: parliamentary systems like the UK fuse legislative and executive functions, with the executive (the cabinet) drawn from and accountable to the legislature.', highlights: ['Formalized by Montesquieu in 1748', 'Three branches: legislative, executive, judicial', 'Built on a system of checks and balances between branches', 'US Constitution is a strict example; UK parliamentary system fuses branches', 'Judicial review lets courts strike down laws deemed unconstitutional'] },
    { id: 'electoral-systems', topic: 'Politics', title: 'First-Past-the-Post vs. Proportional Representation', category: 'Electoral systems', summary: 'Two dominant ways democracies translate votes into seats — and why they produce very different party landscapes.', content: 'Under first-past-the-post (FPTP), used in the US, UK, and India, the candidate with the most votes in a district wins the seat outright, even without a majority — this tends to produce two dominant parties (Duverger\'s Law) because smaller parties rarely win individual districts. Proportional representation (PR), used across most of continental Europe, allocates seats based on each party\'s overall vote share, which tends to produce multi-party coalitions. Mixed systems, like Germany\'s, combine both: voters cast a ballot for a local candidate and a separate ballot for a party list.', highlights: ['FPTP: whoever gets the most local votes wins the seat outright', 'PR: seats are allocated based on a party\'s overall vote share', 'Duverger\'s Law: FPTP tends to produce two dominant parties', 'PR systems tend to produce multi-party coalition governments', 'Germany uses a mixed system combining both approaches'] },
    { id: 'un-security-council-veto', topic: 'Politics', title: 'The UN Security Council Veto', category: 'International institutions', summary: 'Five countries can single-handedly block any UN Security Council resolution, a power baked in since 1945.', content: 'The UN Security Council has five permanent members — the US, UK, France, Russia, and China — each holding veto power over substantive resolutions, a structure agreed at the 1945 founding to secure their participation in the new organization. A single "no" vote from any of the five blocks a resolution regardless of how the other members vote, including the ten elected non-permanent members. This has frequently paralyzed the Council on major conflicts, since any permanent member can shield itself or an ally from binding action.', highlights: ['Five permanent members: US, UK, France, Russia, China', 'Each holds an absolute veto over substantive resolutions', 'Established in 1945 to secure great-power participation in the UN', 'A single veto blocks a resolution regardless of other votes', '10 elected non-permanent members serve two-year terms without veto power'] },
    { id: 'federalism-vs-unitary', topic: 'Politics', title: 'Federalism vs. Unitary States', category: 'State structure', summary: 'Federal systems split sovereignty between national and regional governments; unitary states concentrate it centrally.', content: 'In a federal system — the US, Germany, India, Brazil — power is constitutionally divided between a national government and constituent states or provinces, each with their own areas of authority that the central government generally cannot override. In a unitary state — France, Japan, most of the world\'s countries — sovereignty rests with the central government, which may delegate authority to local governments but can also revoke it. The choice often reflects history: federations frequently emerge from the union of previously separate or diverse territories (like the original 13 American colonies), while unitary states often evolved from a single historical center of power.', highlights: ['Federal systems constitutionally divide power between national and regional governments', 'Unitary states concentrate sovereignty centrally, delegating power at will', 'The US, Germany, India, and Brazil are federations', 'France, Japan, and most countries are unitary states', 'Federations often form from unions of previously separate territories'] },
    { id: 'schengen-area', topic: 'Politics', title: 'The Schengen Area', category: 'Regional integration', summary: 'A 29-country zone in Europe where internal border checks have been abolished, even for countries outside the EU.', content: 'Named after the 1985 agreement signed in the small Luxembourg village of Schengen, the Schengen Area allows passport-free travel across 29 European countries — including non-EU members Norway, Iceland, Switzerland, and Liechtenstein — while maintaining a common external border with stricter joint controls. It is a separate legal framework from the European Union itself: not all EU members are in Schengen (Ireland opted out; Cyprus has not yet joined), and not all Schengen members are in the EU. The system periodically reintroduces temporary internal checks during crises, such as the 2015 migration surge or COVID-19.', highlights: ['Named after a 1985 agreement signed in Schengen, Luxembourg', '29 member countries with passport-free internal travel', 'Includes non-EU members: Norway, Iceland, Switzerland, Liechtenstein', 'Legally distinct from EU membership — the two lists don\'t fully overlap', 'Internal checks can be temporarily reintroduced during crises'] },
    { id: 'gerrymandering', topic: 'Politics', title: 'Gerrymandering', category: 'Electoral systems', summary: 'The practice of drawing electoral district boundaries to favor a particular party, named after an 1812 Massachusetts governor.', content: 'The term originated in 1812 when Massachusetts Governor Elbridge Gerry signed off on a state senate district so contorted that a cartoonist drew it as a salamander — combining "Gerry" and "salamander" into "gerrymander." Modern techniques include "packing" (concentrating opposing voters into few districts to waste their votes) and "cracking" (spreading them thinly across many districts so they never form a majority). Advances in mapping software and granular voter data have made gerrymandering far more precise since the 1990s, and US courts have repeatedly wrestled with whether partisan (as opposed to racial) gerrymandering is something courts can even rule on.', highlights: ['Term coined in 1812 after Governor Elbridge Gerry\'s contorted district', 'Combines "Gerry" + "salamander" from the district\'s shape', '"Packing" concentrates opposing voters into few districts', '"Cracking" spreads opposing voters thin across many districts', 'Modern mapping software has made the practice far more precise'] },
    { id: 'eu-legislative-process', topic: 'Politics', title: 'How EU Laws Get Made', category: 'International institutions', summary: 'EU legislation requires three institutions to agree — a structure unlike any single national government.', content: 'Unlike a national parliament, the EU\'s "ordinary legislative procedure" requires agreement between three bodies: the European Commission (the only body that can propose new legislation), the European Parliament (directly elected by EU citizens), and the Council of the EU (government ministers from each member state). A proposal must pass both the Parliament and the Council, often after multiple negotiating rounds, before becoming law. This deliberately slow, consensus-driven design reflects the EU\'s nature as a union of sovereign states rather than a single federal government.', highlights: ['Three institutions: European Commission, European Parliament, Council of the EU', 'Only the Commission can formally propose new legislation', 'Both Parliament and Council must approve a proposal', 'Designed to balance citizen representation with state sovereignty', 'Multiple negotiating rounds ("readings") are common before passage'] },
    { id: 'filibuster', topic: 'Politics', title: 'The Senate Filibuster', category: 'Legislative procedure', summary: 'A US Senate tactic that lets a minority of senators block a vote indefinitely unless 60 of 100 agree to end debate.', content: 'The filibuster exploits the US Senate\'s tradition of unlimited debate: rather than a simple majority, ending debate on most legislation requires invoking "cloture," which needs 60 of 100 votes. This means a cohesive minority of just 41 senators can block most bills regardless of majority support. The most famous historical filibusters include Strom Thurmond\'s 24-hour, 18-minute speech against the 1957 Civil Rights Act — still the longest individual filibuster on record. Various exceptions, like "budget reconciliation," allow certain bills to pass with a simple majority, which is why major tax and spending legislation is often written to qualify under those rules.', highlights: ['Ending debate ("cloture") requires 60 of 100 Senate votes', 'A minority of 41 senators can block most legislation', 'Strom Thurmond\'s 1957 filibuster lasted 24 hours and 18 minutes — the record', 'Budget reconciliation allows some bills to pass by simple majority', 'The filibuster is a Senate tradition, not a constitutional requirement'] },
    { id: 'parliamentary-vs-presidential', topic: 'Politics', title: 'Parliamentary vs. Presidential Systems', category: 'State structure', summary: 'Whether the head of government is drawn from the legislature or elected separately shapes how easily governments can fall.', content: 'In a parliamentary system (UK, Japan, India), the head of government — typically a prime minister — is drawn from and accountable to the legislature, and can be removed via a vote of no confidence, sometimes triggering early elections. In a presidential system (US, Brazil, most of Latin America), the head of government is elected separately from the legislature for a fixed term, creating a clearer separation but also more potential for gridlock when the executive and legislature are controlled by different parties. Semi-presidential systems (France) split executive power between an elected president and a prime minister who answers to parliament.', highlights: ['Parliamentary systems: PM is drawn from and accountable to the legislature', 'Presidential systems: head of government elected separately for a fixed term', 'No-confidence votes can remove a PM and trigger early elections', 'Presidential systems are more prone to executive-legislative gridlock', 'Semi-presidential systems (France) split power between a president and PM'] },
    { id: 'nato-article-5', topic: 'Politics', title: 'NATO Article 5', category: 'International institutions', summary: 'The collective defense clause stating that an attack on one NATO member is an attack on all — invoked only once, after 9/11.', content: 'Article 5 of the 1949 North Atlantic Treaty commits each member to consider an armed attack against any one member as an attack against all, and to assist the attacked party "as it deems necessary," which notably leaves the specific response (including whether to use military force) up to each individual member. Despite being the alliance\'s defining principle throughout the Cold War, it has only been formally invoked once — by the United States after the September 11, 2001 attacks — leading other NATO members to contribute forces to operations in Afghanistan.', highlights: ['Article 5 of the 1949 North Atlantic Treaty', 'Treats an attack on one member as an attack on all', 'Leaves the specific response up to each member nation', 'Invoked only once: by the US after September 11, 2001', 'Led to NATO involvement in the war in Afghanistan'] },
    { id: 'referendums-vs-representative-democracy', topic: 'Politics', title: 'Referendums vs. Representative Democracy', category: 'Democratic theory', summary: 'Direct votes on specific questions sit uneasily alongside systems built around elected representatives.', content: 'Referendums let citizens vote directly on a specific question rather than delegating the decision to elected representatives — Switzerland holds them more frequently than almost any other country, often several times a year on issues ranging from constitutional amendments to local zoning. Critics argue referendums can reduce complex policy tradeoffs to a binary yes/no choice and are vulnerable to campaign messaging or low turnout skewing results, as debated extensively after the UK\'s 2016 Brexit referendum. Supporters counter that they provide direct legitimacy that representative votes alone cannot, especially for fundamental constitutional questions.', highlights: ['Switzerland holds referendums more often than almost any country', 'Reduce complex decisions to a binary yes/no vote', 'The UK\'s 2016 Brexit vote intensified debate over referendum design', 'Often required specifically for constitutional changes', 'Can be vulnerable to low turnout or one-sided campaign spending'] },

    /* ════════════ ART ════════════ */
    { id: 'impressionism', topic: 'Art', title: 'Impressionism', category: 'Movement', summary: 'A 19th-century movement that prioritized fleeting light and color over precise detail, named as an insult.', content: 'Impressionism emerged in 1870s France among artists like Monet, Renoir, Degas, and Pissarro who rejected the rigid realism demanded by the official Paris Salon. The name itself was coined mockingly by critic Louis Leroy in 1874, referencing Monet\'s painting "Impression, Sunrise" — he meant it as an insult, implying the work looked unfinished. The artists embraced the term anyway. Their innovations included painting outdoors (en plein air) to capture changing light directly, visible loose brushstrokes, and a focus on everyday modern life rather than historical or mythological subjects.', highlights: ['Emerged in 1870s France among Monet, Renoir, Degas, and Pissarro', 'Named mockingly by critic Louis Leroy in 1874', 'Named after Monet\'s painting "Impression, Sunrise"', 'Pioneered painting outdoors (en plein air) to capture changing light', 'Rejected the Paris Salon\'s demand for polished historical realism'] },
    { id: 'the-renaissance', topic: 'Art', title: 'The Renaissance', category: 'Era', summary: 'A roughly 300-year rebirth of classical learning and naturalistic art that began in 14th-century Florence.', content: 'The Renaissance ("rebirth") began in Florence around the 1300s–1400s, fueled by renewed interest in classical Greek and Roman texts, the wealth of merchant families like the Medici, and technical innovations like linear perspective, which let artists render three-dimensional space convincingly on a flat surface for the first time. Figures like Brunelleschi (who formalized linear perspective), Masaccio, and later Leonardo da Vinci, Michelangelo, and Raphael transformed art from the flatter, symbolic style of the medieval period into something closer to optical realism, grounded in anatomy, mathematics, and direct observation.', highlights: ['Began in Florence around the 1300s–1400s', 'Funded substantially by wealthy merchant families like the Medici', 'Brunelleschi formalized linear perspective in painting', 'Marked a shift from symbolic medieval art toward optical realism', 'Leonardo da Vinci, Michelangelo, and Raphael define its peak ("High Renaissance")'] },
    { id: 'cubism', topic: 'Art', title: 'Cubism', category: 'Movement', summary: 'A movement co-founded by Picasso and Braque that shattered single-viewpoint perspective into multiple angles at once.', content: 'Cubism emerged around 1907–1908 in Paris, pioneered jointly by Pablo Picasso and Georges Braque, who worked so closely in its early years that their paintings are sometimes hard to tell apart. Rather than depicting a subject from one fixed viewpoint, Cubist paintings fracture it into geometric facets shown from multiple angles simultaneously, rejecting the single-point perspective that had dominated Western art since the Renaissance. "Analytic Cubism" (more fragmented, monochrome) gave way around 1912 to "Synthetic Cubism," which introduced collage elements like newspaper clippings — among the first uses of collage in fine art.', highlights: ['Co-founded by Picasso and Braque around 1907–1908', 'Depicts subjects from multiple viewpoints simultaneously', 'Rejected single-point perspective used since the Renaissance', 'Split into "Analytic" (1907–1912) and "Synthetic" Cubism phases', 'Synthetic Cubism introduced collage into fine art'] },
    { id: 'mona-lisa-fame', topic: 'Art', title: 'Why the Mona Lisa Is So Famous', category: 'Iconic works', summary: 'Leonardo\'s portrait was relatively obscure for centuries — its global fame is largely a 20th-century phenomenon.', content: 'Painted by Leonardo da Vinci around 1503–1519, the Mona Lisa was admired by art experts but not a global icon for most of its history. Its fame surged dramatically after it was stolen from the Louvre in 1911 by an Italian handyman who believed it should belong to Italy — the theft made international headlines, and the painting\'s recovery two years later cemented its mystique. Its small size (77 × 53 cm, smaller than most expect) and the subject\'s ambiguous half-smile, created using Leonardo\'s subtle sfumato shading technique, continue to fuel endless analysis and parody.', highlights: ['Painted by Leonardo da Vinci, roughly 1503–1519', 'Was respected but not globally famous until the 20th century', 'Stolen from the Louvre in 1911, recovered two years later', 'The theft and media coverage drove its modern fame', 'Measures only 77 × 53 cm — smaller than most people expect'] },
    { id: 'abstract-expressionism', topic: 'Art', title: 'Abstract Expressionism', category: 'Movement', summary: 'A mid-20th-century American movement, including Jackson Pollock\'s drip paintings, that made the act of painting itself the subject.', content: 'Abstract Expressionism developed in New York in the 1940s–1950s as the first major American art movement to gain global influence, partly because World War II had displaced the art world\'s center away from Paris. It split loosely into "action painting," exemplified by Jackson Pollock\'s gestural drip technique — laying canvases on the floor and pouring or flinging paint — and "color field painting," exemplified by Mark Rothko\'s large, glowing blocks of color meant to evoke a direct emotional or contemplative response rather than represent anything literal.', highlights: ['Developed in New York during the 1940s–1950s', 'First major American art movement with global influence', 'Jackson Pollock pioneered gestural "drip" action painting', 'Mark Rothko exemplified contemplative "color field" painting', 'Emphasized the physical act of painting and emotional response over representation'] },
    { id: 'art-nouveau', topic: 'Art', title: 'Art Nouveau', category: 'Movement', summary: 'A decorative style defined by flowing, organic lines inspired by plants and natural forms, popular from roughly 1890 to 1910.', content: 'Art Nouveau ("new art") swept across Europe and the US from about 1890 to 1910, characterized by sinuous, whiplash curves drawn from plant tendrils, flowers, and flowing hair. It deliberately blurred the line between fine art and applied design — the same aesthetic appeared in paintings, but also in architecture (Antoni Gaudí\'s Barcelona buildings), furniture, jewelry, and the iconic Paris Métro entrances designed by Hector Guimard. The movement was partly a reaction against industrial mass production, championing handcrafted, unified design across every object in a space.', highlights: ['Flourished roughly 1890 to 1910 across Europe and the US', 'Defined by sinuous, organic lines drawn from plants and nature', 'Spanned painting, architecture, furniture, and jewelry alike', 'Antoni Gaudí\'s Barcelona buildings are landmark examples', 'Partly a reaction against industrial mass production'] },
    { id: 'bauhaus', topic: 'Art', title: 'The Bauhaus', category: 'Movement', summary: 'A German art school (1919–1933) that fused craft, art, and industrial design — shut down by the Nazis as "degenerate."', content: 'Founded by architect Walter Gropius in Weimar, Germany in 1919, the Bauhaus aimed to dissolve the boundary between fine art and functional craft, training students in both simultaneously and championing the idea that good design should serve mass production, not just elite taste. Its minimalist, geometric aesthetic — clean lines, primary colors, and a "form follows function" ethos — became foundational to modern architecture, furniture, and graphic design. The school relocated twice under political pressure before the Nazi regime forced its closure in 1933, scattering its faculty (including Gropius, Mies van der Rohe, and Kandinsky) to teaching posts around the world, especially the US.', highlights: ['Founded by Walter Gropius in Weimar, Germany, in 1919', 'Fused fine art training with functional, industrial design', 'Championed "form follows function" minimalism', 'Closed by the Nazi regime in 1933 as "degenerate"', 'Its exiled faculty spread Bauhaus ideas to US architecture and design schools'] },
    { id: 'ukiyo-e', topic: 'Art', title: 'Ukiyo-e (Japanese Woodblock Prints)', category: 'Tradition', summary: 'Edo-period Japanese prints, including Hokusai\'s "Great Wave," that directly shaped European Impressionism.', content: 'Ukiyo-e ("pictures of the floating world") flourished in Japan from the 17th to 19th centuries, depicting kabuki actors, courtesans, landscapes, and everyday urban life through woodblock printing, which allowed inexpensive mass production. Katsushika Hokusai\'s "The Great Wave off Kanagawa" (c. 1831) is the most recognizable example worldwide. When Japan reopened to trade in the 1850s–1860s, ukiyo-e prints flooded into Europe, often literally used as packing material for porcelain — and their flat color planes, bold outlines, and asymmetric compositions directly influenced Impressionist and Post-Impressionist artists like Monet, Van Gogh, and Degas, a craze known as "Japonisme."', highlights: ['Flourished in Japan from the 17th to 19th centuries', 'Hokusai\'s "The Great Wave off Kanagawa" (c. 1831) is the iconic example', 'Mass-produced via woodblock printing, making art widely affordable', 'Reached Europe en masse after Japan reopened trade in the 1850s–60s', 'Directly influenced Monet, Van Gogh, and Degas ("Japonisme")'] },
    { id: 'surrealism', topic: 'Art', title: 'Surrealism', category: 'Movement', summary: 'A movement built on Freudian dream theory, using bizarre, illogical imagery to access the unconscious mind.', content: 'Surrealism began with André Breton\'s 1924 Surrealist Manifesto, drawing heavily on Sigmund Freud\'s theories of dreams and the unconscious. Artists used techniques like "automatic drawing," meant to bypass conscious control and let the unconscious guide the hand, alongside deliberately illogical, dreamlike imagery. Salvador Dalí\'s melting clocks in "The Persistence of Memory" (1931) and René Magritte\'s impossible scenes (a man\'s face obscured by a floating apple, in "The Son of Man") remain the movement\'s most recognized works, prizing strangeness and the irrational over realism or formal beauty.', highlights: ['Founded on André Breton\'s 1924 Surrealist Manifesto', 'Drew heavily on Freud\'s theories of dreams and the unconscious', 'Used "automatic drawing" to bypass conscious artistic control', 'Dalí\'s "The Persistence of Memory" (1931) is a defining work', 'Magritte\'s impossible, dreamlike scenes are equally iconic'] },
    { id: 'pop-art', topic: 'Art', title: 'Pop Art', category: 'Movement', summary: 'A movement that elevated advertising, comic strips, and supermarket products to fine-art subject matter.', content: 'Pop Art emerged in the mid-1950s in Britain and gained massive momentum in 1960s America, treating mass media and consumer culture as legitimate, even celebrated, subject matter for fine art — a direct contrast to Abstract Expressionism\'s introspective seriousness. Andy Warhol\'s repeated silkscreen prints of Campbell\'s Soup cans (1962) and Marilyn Monroe both critiqued and embraced the repetitive, commercialized nature of modern consumer society. Roy Lichtenstein similarly blew up comic-book panels, complete with their printed dot patterns (Ben-Day dots), into large-scale paintings, blurring the line between "high" and "low" culture.', highlights: ['Emerged in mid-1950s Britain, peaked in 1960s America', 'Treated advertising and consumer products as fine-art subjects', 'Andy Warhol\'s Campbell\'s Soup cans (1962) are the movement\'s icon', 'Roy Lichtenstein enlarged comic-book panels, including printed dot patterns', 'Deliberately blurred the line between "high" and "low" culture'] },
    { id: 'chiaroscuro', topic: 'Art', title: 'Chiaroscuro', category: 'Technique', summary: 'A dramatic light-and-shadow technique perfected by Caravaggio that gives flat paintings a startling sense of depth.', content: 'Chiaroscuro (Italian for "light-dark") uses strong contrasts between light and shadow to model three-dimensional form and create dramatic emphasis within a painting. While the technique appears earlier in Renaissance art, Caravaggio pushed it to an extreme in the late 1500s–early 1600s, often called "tenebrism" — plunging most of the canvas into near-total darkness while a single, intense light source illuminates the central action, as in "The Calling of Saint Matthew" (1599–1600). The technique heightens emotional intensity and theatricality, and was hugely influential on later Baroque painters like Rembrandt.', highlights: ['Italian for "light-dark"', 'Uses strong light/shadow contrast to model 3D form on a flat surface', 'Caravaggio\'s extreme version is often called "tenebrism"', '"The Calling of Saint Matthew" (1599–1600) is a defining example', 'Heavily influenced later Baroque painters, including Rembrandt'] },
    { id: 'nft-art-market', topic: 'Art', title: 'NFTs & the Digital Art Market', category: 'Contemporary', summary: 'Non-fungible tokens let digital art carry a unique, verifiable certificate of ownership on a blockchain.', content: 'An NFT (non-fungible token) is a unique entry on a blockchain that certifies ownership of a specific digital (or sometimes physical) asset — unlike cryptocurrency, where each unit is interchangeable, each NFT is distinct and traceable to a single owner. The market exploded into mainstream attention in March 2021 when Beeple\'s digital collage "Everydays: The First 5000 Days" sold at Christie\'s for $69.3 million, the first major auction house sale of a purely digital, NFT-backed artwork. The NFT market subsequently crashed from its 2021 peak, but it permanently raised questions about how ownership, scarcity, and authenticity apply to art that can otherwise be copied infinitely for free.', highlights: ['NFTs are unique blockchain entries certifying ownership of a digital asset', 'Differ from cryptocurrency in being non-interchangeable ("non-fungible")', 'Beeple\'s "Everydays" sold for $69.3 million at Christie\'s in March 2021', 'First major NFT-backed artwork sold at a traditional auction house', 'Raised lasting questions about scarcity and ownership of infinitely copyable digital art'] },

    /* ════════════ STOCK OPTIONS ════════════ */
    { id: 'call-vs-put', topic: 'Stock Options', title: 'Call Options vs. Put Options', category: 'Fundamentals', summary: 'A call gives the right to buy a stock at a set price; a put gives the right to sell — the two basic building blocks of options.', content: 'A call option gives its holder the right (but not the obligation) to buy 100 shares of the underlying stock at a fixed "strike price" before expiration — buyers purchase calls when they expect the stock to rise. A put option gives the right to sell at the strike price, used when expecting the stock to fall, or to hedge an existing position like insurance. The seller ("writer") of either contract takes on the obligation if the buyer chooses to exercise: a call writer must sell shares at the strike price, and a put writer must buy them, regardless of where the market price has moved.', highlights: ['A call = right to buy at the strike price before expiration', 'A put = right to sell at the strike price before expiration', 'US equity option contracts typically represent 100 shares', 'Buyers have rights; sellers ("writers") take on obligations', 'Puts are commonly used to hedge an existing stock position'] },
    { id: 'strike-price-intrinsic-value', topic: 'Stock Options', title: 'Strike Price & Intrinsic Value', category: 'Fundamentals', summary: 'Whether an option is "in," "at," or "out of the money" depends entirely on how its strike compares to the current stock price.', content: 'The strike price is the fixed price at which an option can be exercised. A call is "in the money" (ITM) when the stock trades above the strike — it has intrinsic value because exercising it would let the holder buy below market price. It\'s "out of the money" (OTM) when the stock is below the strike, meaning exercising would be pointless, and "at the money" (ATM) when the two are roughly equal. For puts, the relationship flips: a put is ITM when the stock is below the strike. An option\'s total premium is the sum of its intrinsic value (if any) and its "time value," which reflects the remaining chance the option could move further into the money before expiring.', highlights: ['Strike price: the fixed price at which the option can be exercised', 'A call is "in the money" when the stock price is above the strike', 'A put is "in the money" when the stock price is below the strike', 'Option premium = intrinsic value + time value', 'Out-of-the-money options have zero intrinsic value, only time value'] },
    { id: 'the-greeks', topic: 'Stock Options', title: 'The Greeks (Delta, Gamma, Theta, Vega)', category: 'Risk metrics', summary: 'A set of risk measures that describe exactly how an option\'s price reacts to changes in the stock, time, and volatility.', content: 'Delta measures how much an option\'s price moves for a $1 move in the underlying stock — a delta of 0.50 means the option gains roughly $0.50 for every $1 the stock rises. Gamma measures how fast delta itself changes as the stock moves, capturing the curvature of the option\'s price sensitivity. Theta quantifies time decay — how much value the option loses purely from one day passing, all else equal, which accelerates sharply as expiration nears. Vega measures sensitivity to changes in implied volatility: option prices generally rise when expected future volatility rises, even if the stock price itself doesn\'t move.', highlights: ['Delta: price change per $1 move in the underlying stock', 'Gamma: the rate of change of delta itself', 'Theta: daily value lost purely from time passing ("time decay")', 'Vega: sensitivity to changes in implied volatility', 'Theta decay accelerates sharply in the final weeks before expiration'] },
    { id: 'expiration-assignment', topic: 'Stock Options', title: 'Expiration & Assignment', category: 'Mechanics', summary: 'Options don\'t last forever — what happens to a contract depends on whether it\'s in or out of the money when it expires.', content: 'Every option contract has an expiration date, after which it ceases to exist. If an option is out of the money at expiration, it simply expires worthless and the buyer loses the premium paid. If it\'s in the money, most brokers will automatically exercise it on the holder\'s behalf unless instructed otherwise. "Assignment" is what happens to the option seller when a buyer exercises: a short call seller is forced to deliver (sell) shares at the strike, while a short put seller is forced to buy shares at the strike — sometimes unexpectedly, which is why selling uncovered ("naked") options carries open-ended risk.', highlights: ['Options that expire out of the money become worthless', 'In-the-money options are typically auto-exercised at expiration', '"Assignment" forces the option seller to fulfill the contract', 'A short call assignment forces the seller to deliver shares', 'A short put assignment forces the seller to buy shares'] },
    { id: 'covered-call', topic: 'Stock Options', title: 'The Covered Call Strategy', category: 'Strategies', summary: 'A way to generate income from stock you already own by selling someone else the right to buy it from you.', content: 'A covered call involves owning at least 100 shares of a stock and selling a call option against those shares, collecting the option\'s premium immediately as income. If the stock stays below the strike price, the call expires worthless and the seller keeps both the shares and the premium. If the stock rises above the strike, the shares may get "called away" (sold) at the strike price — meaning the seller still profits up to that price plus the premium, but forfeits any further upside beyond the strike. It\'s considered one of the lower-risk options strategies because the stock position itself "covers" the obligation, unlike selling a naked call.', highlights: ['Requires owning at least 100 shares of the underlying stock', 'Generates immediate income from the option premium', 'Caps further upside if the stock rises above the strike', 'Shares can be "called away" (sold) if the option finishes in the money', 'Considered lower-risk since the stock position covers the obligation'] },
    { id: 'black-scholes-model', topic: 'Stock Options', title: 'The Black-Scholes Model', category: 'Pricing theory', summary: 'The 1973 formula that gave options trading a standardized, mathematical price — and won its creators a Nobel Prize.', content: 'Developed by Fischer Black and Myron Scholes (with key contributions from Robert Merton) and published in 1973, the Black-Scholes model provided the first widely used formula for calculating a theoretical "fair price" for European-style options, based on five inputs: the stock price, strike price, time to expiration, risk-free interest rate, and volatility. Its publication coincided almost exactly with the opening of the Chicago Board Options Exchange (CBOE) in 1973, and the model rapidly became the industry standard, fueling explosive growth in options trading. Scholes and Merton received the 1997 Nobel Prize in Economics for the work (Black had died in 1995 and was ineligible).', highlights: ['Developed by Fischer Black and Myron Scholes, published in 1973', 'Robert Merton made key contributions to the underlying math', 'Uses five inputs: stock price, strike, time, interest rate, volatility', 'Published the same year the CBOE — the first options exchange — opened', 'Scholes and Merton won the 1997 Nobel Prize in Economics'] },
    { id: 'implied-volatility', topic: 'Stock Options', title: 'Implied Volatility', category: 'Pricing theory', summary: 'A number derived from option prices themselves that reflects how much the market expects a stock to swing in the future.', content: 'Implied volatility (IV) is calculated by working a pricing model like Black-Scholes backward: instead of starting with volatility to find a price, you start with the option\'s actual market price and solve for the volatility level that would justify it. Unlike historical volatility, which looks backward at how much a stock has already moved, IV reflects the market\'s forward-looking expectation. IV tends to spike before known events like earnings reports, and the VIX index — often called the market\'s "fear gauge" — is itself built from the implied volatility of S&P 500 index options.', highlights: ['Derived by working an options pricing model backward from market price', 'Reflects forward-looking expectations, unlike backward-looking historical volatility', 'Tends to spike ahead of known events like earnings reports', 'The VIX "fear gauge" is built from S&P 500 options\' implied volatility', 'Higher implied volatility generally means higher option premiums'] },
    { id: 'employee-stock-options', topic: 'Stock Options', title: 'Employee Stock Options (ESOs)', category: 'Compensation', summary: 'Company-granted options that vest over time, distinct from the listed options traded on public exchanges.', content: 'Employee stock options (ESOs) grant employees the right to buy company shares at a fixed "grant price," typically vesting gradually over several years (a common schedule is a one-year "cliff" followed by monthly or quarterly vesting over four years total) as an incentive to stay and contribute to the company\'s growth. Unlike exchange-listed options, ESOs aren\'t traded on a market, usually can\'t be sold to anyone else, and typically expire if an employee leaves the company within a short window (often 90 days) unless exercised. Their value depends heavily on the company eventually being acquired or going public, since private company shares otherwise have no liquid market.', highlights: ['Grant employees the right to buy shares at a fixed grant price', 'Common vesting schedule: 1-year cliff, then gradual vesting over 4 years', 'Unlike listed options, ESOs cannot be traded on an exchange', 'Usually expire ~90 days after an employee leaves the company', 'Value is tied to an eventual acquisition or IPO for private companies'] },
    { id: 'straddle-strangle', topic: 'Stock Options', title: 'Straddles & Strangles', category: 'Strategies', summary: 'Strategies that profit from big price swings in either direction, without betting on which way the stock will move.', content: 'A long straddle involves buying both a call and a put at the same strike price and expiration — it profits if the stock makes a large move in either direction, since one leg will gain more than enough to offset the other\'s loss, but it loses money if the stock stays flat, since both options decay over time. A strangle is a cheaper variant using an out-of-the-money call and an out-of-the-money put (different strikes), requiring an even bigger move to profit but costing less upfront. Both are popular ahead of binary events like earnings announcements or major court rulings, where direction is uncertain but a large move is expected.', highlights: ['Straddle: buy a call and put at the same strike and expiration', 'Strangle: buy an OTM call and OTM put at different strikes', 'Both profit from large moves in either direction', 'Both lose value if the stock stays flat (time decay on both legs)', 'Commonly used ahead of earnings or other binary, high-uncertainty events'] },
    { id: 'time-decay-theta', topic: 'Stock Options', title: 'Time Decay (Theta Decay)', category: 'Risk metrics', summary: 'Options are a melting ice cube — they lose value purely from the passage of time, accelerating as expiration nears.', content: 'Every option has a finite lifespan, and part of its price — the "time value" — reflects the probability that it could still move into (or further into) the money before expiring. As that window shrinks, time value erodes even if the stock price doesn\'t move at all, a process called time decay or theta decay. Decay isn\'t linear: it\'s relatively slow for options with months left, but accelerates dramatically in the final 30 days, and most sharply in the final week, which is why option sellers often prefer shorter-dated contracts and buyers of far-OTM options need a stock move to happen quickly.', highlights: ['Time value erodes purely from the passage of time', 'Decay accelerates sharply in the final 30 days before expiration', 'It is fastest of all in the final week before expiration', 'Affects out-of-the-money options most severely in relative terms', 'A key reason option sellers often favor shorter-dated contracts'] },
    { id: 'american-vs-european-options', topic: 'Stock Options', title: 'American-Style vs. European-Style Options', category: 'Fundamentals', summary: 'The terms have nothing to do with geography — they describe whether an option can be exercised early or only at expiration.', content: 'American-style options can be exercised at any point up until expiration, while European-style options can only be exercised exactly on the expiration date itself, regardless of where they are actually traded. Confusingly, the names are about exercise rules, not location: most US equity options are American-style, while most US index options, like those on the S&P 500 (SPX), are European-style. Because the right to exercise early has some value, American-style options are theoretically worth slightly more than otherwise-identical European-style ones, all else equal — though in practice early exercise is fairly rare except in specific situations like capturing a dividend.', highlights: ['American-style: can be exercised any time before expiration', 'European-style: can only be exercised on the expiration date itself', 'The names describe exercise rules, not geography', 'Most US stock options are American-style; major US index options are European-style', 'Early-exercise flexibility gives American options slightly more theoretical value'] },
    { id: 'options-margin', topic: 'Stock Options', title: 'Margin Requirements for Options', category: 'Risk management', summary: 'Selling uncovered options requires posting collateral, since the potential loss can vastly exceed the premium collected.', content: 'When buying an option, the maximum loss is simply the premium paid — which is why buying calls or puts requires no special margin beyond the purchase cost. Selling options is different: a covered call requires only owning the underlying shares, but selling an uncovered ("naked") call or put requires posting margin, because the brokerage needs assurance the seller can cover a potentially large loss if the stock moves sharply against the position. Naked call selling carries theoretically unlimited risk, since a stock price has no upper bound, which is why many brokers restrict it to experienced traders with sufficiently funded margin accounts.', highlights: ['Buying options requires no margin beyond the premium paid', 'Covered calls require only owning the underlying shares', 'Naked (uncovered) option selling requires posting margin collateral', 'Naked call selling carries theoretically unlimited risk', 'Brokers often restrict naked option selling to experienced, well-funded accounts'] },
  ];
